.ie \n(.g .ds Aq \(aq
.el .ds Aq '
.TH ox-invalidate 1  "ox-invalidate " 
.SH NAME
ox\-invalidate \- Invalidate cached outputs
.SH SYNOPSIS
\fBox\-invalidate\fR [\fB\-\-rule\fR] [\fB\-\-output\fR] [\fB\-\-cascade\fR] [\fB\-\-all\fR] [\fB\-n\fR|\fB\-\-dry\-run\fR] [\fB\-\-keep\-outputs\fR] [\fB\-\-json\fR] [\fB\-f\fR|\fB\-\-file\fR] [\fB\-h\fR|\fB\-\-help\fR] 
.SH DESCRIPTION
Invalidate cached outputs
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-\-rule\fR \fI<RULE>\fR
Filter by rule name (exact match or /regex/)
.TP
\fB\-\-output\fR \fI<PATH>\fR
Specific output file paths to invalidate (repeatable)
.TP
\fB\-\-cascade\fR
Also invalidate all downstream rules
.TP
\fB\-\-all\fR
Invalidate all cache entries
.TP
\fB\-n\fR, \fB\-\-dry\-run\fR
Show what would be invalidated without modifying the cache
.TP
\fB\-\-keep\-outputs\fR
Keep output files on disk (only clear cache entries).

By default, `ox invalidate` deletes output files so that subsequent runs rebuild them regardless of cache validation mode.  With `\-\-keep\-outputs`, only the cache database entries are removed.
.TP
\fB\-\-json\fR
Output results as JSON
.TP
\fB\-f\fR, \fB\-\-file\fR \fI<FILE>\fR [default: Oxymakefile.toml]
Oxymakefile path
.TP
\fB\-h\fR, \fB\-\-help\fR
Print help (see a summary with \*(Aq\-h\*(Aq)
